  "text": "The CD157, CD38 and Aplysia cyclase polypeptides share a central core with 25-30% amino acid sequence similarity [CITATION_1] 18, 19) . The determinants of their diverse protein topology reside instead in the N-and Cterminal modifications. Being a soluble protein, the Aplysia cyclase has an N-terminal signal peptide. A longer form of this hydrophobic region is found in CD38, accounting for its being type II membrane protein, whereas CD157 is GPIanchored, by virtue of the presence of a ninth exon encoding the hydrophobic signal for GPI attachment. Thus, changes in BST-1/CD157 exon 9 and CD38 exon 1 are responsible for membrane attachment of the mammalian ADPRCs.",
